- `IntegrationFormValues` in `src/ui/components/integrations/directory/create/types.ts` is an **intersection** of:
  - `Record<string, IntegrationFieldValue>`
  - and a `Partial<Record<...>>` that includes a narrower type for `name` (string | undefined), `url`, etc.
- When you index with `k` in `initialValues[k] = val`, `k` is a union of keys (`'donationPagesOnly' | 'listIds' | 'name' | 'scopeId'`).  
  TypeScript computes `IntegrationFormValues[k]` as the **intersection** of those types, which collapses to `IntegrationFieldValue & (string | undefined)` (effectively `string`).
- That means even in the default case where the value is a boolean or string[], TS still thinks the target is a string, so it errors. That’s why you see this in multiple files—any place indexing `IntegrationFormValues` with a key union hits the same intersection behavior.

Why the error text says `{}`  
`val` is inferred as `{}` in some branches because of the broad `Record<string, any>` + `??` + `isNotNullish` (not a type guard), so the compiler is left with a very weak type that can’t satisfy the narrowed target type.

Config to “make it not error”?

- There isn’t a specific `tsconfig` flag that changes how intersections + indexed access are computed.
- The only config-style way to suppress this is **loosening** `strict` (or using `// @ts-ignore`), which I wouldn’t recommend.

If you want it fixed properly (no config changes), the usual approaches are:
1) Change the type to avoid the intersection trap (e.g. use an index signature that allows `undefined`, and explicit optional props):
```ts
export type IntegrationFormValues = {
  [key: string]: IntegrationFieldValue | undefined;
  actionPageId?: 'all' | string;
  actionPageName?: string;
  campaignId?: 'all' | string;
  campaignName?: string;
  integrationType?: 'actionPages' | 'campaigns';
  slug?: string;
  name?: string;
  url?: string;
};
```
2) Or, if you want minimal change, cast at assignment sites:
```ts
initialValues[k] = val as IntegrationFieldValue;
```

If you want, I can propose a consistent type fix that removes the error across the repo.

